Pick<T, K> and Omit<T, K>

`Pick<T, K>` creates a type with a subset of properties. `Omit<T, K>` creates a type excluding specified properties.

### Pick<T, K>

```typescript
interface User {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  email: string;
  age: number;
  password: string;
}

type PublicUser = Pick<User, "id" | "name" | "email">;
// { id: number; name: string; email: string }

const publicUser: PublicUser = {
  id: 1,
  name: "Alice",
  email: "alice@example.com"
};
```

### How Pick Works

```typescript
type Pick<T, K extends keyof T> = {
  [P in K]: T[P];
};
```

### Omit<T, K>

```typescript
type UserWithoutPassword = Omit<User, "password">;
// { id: number; name: string; email: string; age: number }

const safeUser: UserWithoutPassword = {
  id: 1,
  name: "Alice",
  email: "alice@example.com",
  age: 30
};
```

### How Omit Works

```typescript
type Omit<T, K extends keyof any> = Pick<T, Exclude<keyof T, K>>;
```

### Practical Examples

| Use Case | Utility |
|----------|---------|
| Public API response (remove sensitive fields) | `Omit` |
| Form input (select specific fields) | `Pick` |
| Base type (add fields later) | `Omit` then extend |
| Component props | `Pick` from a larger config |

### Combining with Partial

```typescript
// Allow updating only non-sensitive fields
function updateUserProfile(
  id: number,
  updates: Partial<Omit<User, "id" | "password">>
): void {
  console.log(`Updating profile for user ${id}:`, updates);
}
```

> **Key Point:** `Pick` selects properties, `Omit` excludes them.

